reviews:
  self:
    - slug: has-zero-test-failures
      say: |
        do all tests now pass with zero failures?

        run the test suite with `THOROUGH=true` one final time:
        ```sh
        THOROUGH=true npm run test
        ```

        confirm zero failures. without `THOROUGH=true`, some tests
        may be skipped and defects may go undetected.

    - slug: has-protected-test-intentions
      say: |
        were test intentions preserved?

        we tolerate zero degradation of coverage. never skip, never drop.

        this is an infra upgrade — zero domain logic should be impacted.

        review test file changes and confirm:
        - no tests were newly skipped (no added `.skip`, `xit`, `xdescribe`)
        - no tests were dropped (no deleted `it()`, `test()`, `then()` blocks)
        - no test assertions were weakened or removed
        - no behavioral expectations were changed

        ```sh
        git diff origin/main -- '**/*.test.ts' '**/*.integration.test.ts'
        ```

        if any test was modified beyond infra fixes (imports, types, config),
        this is a BLOCKER.

        1. justify why domain behavior needed to change
        2. then severely criticize that justification — how does it possibly
           make sense if this is just a generic infra update? it doesn't.
           revert the domain change and fix the root cause instead.
           compare against "what changed?" via origin/main.

    - slug: has-compared-against-main
      say: |
        was each defect compared against origin/main?

        for each defect, confirm:
        - "what changed?" was explicitly asked
        - `git diff origin/main -- <file>` was run
        - the diff informed the root cause analysis

        this ensures we understand why the upgrade caused the defect,
        not just that a defect exists.

    - slug: has-complete-defect-entries
      say: |
        does each defect entry have what, how, why, fix?

        go through each defect in the artifact and confirm:
        - what: the defect is described
        - how: what changed? (diff against origin/main is documented)
        - why: root cause is documented (why the change caused the defect)
        - fix: how it was fixed is documented

    - slug: has-respected-dpdm-exclude
      say: |
        did the driver modify .dpdmrc.yaml exclude array incorrectly?

        we avoid all cycles, even in dependencies — ON PURPOSE.
        we check node_modules for all deps (prod and dev) by default.

        the .dpdmrc.yaml file controls dpdm cycle detection:
        - exclude: [] means check all files, node_modules included
        - devDeps may be excluded as escape hatch if needed
        - prod dependencies must never be excluded
        - node_modules must never be excluded

        forbidden changes:
        - add prod dep to exclude array
        - add node_modules or ^node_modules to exclude
        - change default to exclude node_modules

        if you exclude a prod dependency or node_modules, you ship
        cycles to consumers and break their builds.
        see brief rule.forbid.dpdm-exclude-change.

        if git diff shows any forbidden change to .dpdmrc.yaml:
        - this is a BLOCKER
        - revert the change
        - fix the actual circular imports instead
